is success, she contends, was due in large part to his development of pictorial strategies-an epistolary mode of address-marked by a direct, intimate appeal to the viewer, an appeal that also acknowledged the distance and delay that defers the message before it can reach its recipient. As images, often in the form of prints, coursed through an open market, and artists lost direct control over the sale and reception of their work, Germany's chief printmaker navigated the new terrain by creating in his images a balance between legibility and concealment, intimacy and public address.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aCommunication and the artszGermanyxHistoryy16th century. 0aCommunication in artzGermanyxHistoryy16th century. 0aGerman lettersy16th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aVisual communicationzGermanyxHistoryy16th century. 0aWritten communicationzGermanyxHistoryy16th century. 4aAlbrecht Dürer. 4aGerman. 4aaddress. 4aaudience. 4aauthor. 4acommunication. 4ahandwriting. 4aletters. 4apostal system. 4aprints. 4atechnology. 4awriting. 7aART / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2016z978311070422808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2016z978311068860308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226354897423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226354897.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-068860-3  UChP eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-070422-8  UChP eBook-Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles